***LAST CALL TO REGISTER FOR The 10th Annual NYCAASC: Checkpoints!**
If you would like to attend the conference, you must register by TONIGHT at https://www.eventbrite.com/e/10th-annual-nycaasc-registration-22417219507.

With a slew of amazing workshops to choose from this year, as well as our superb performers and keynote speaker, Cathy Dang, #NYCAASC2016 is going to be an incredible experience. We can’t wait to see you all tomorrow!

Vast discussions about the role of the police have been buzzing through the news in recent months. But did you know that, as an individual in the United States, you have various rights and protections when it comes to interacting with law enforcement? At #NYCAASC2016, join Kevin Park in his essential workshop, "Know Your Rights with the Justice Committee", and learn the invaluable info and skills you need to stay safe in police encounters.

As America quickly approaches a critical point for the reproductive rights of millions of current and future mothers, Chi Nguyen invites you to learn about and participate in the process of raising awareness for the upcoming Supreme Court case, Whole Woman’s Health v. Hellerstedt, through the powerful and creative processes of “craftivism”.

#NYCAASC2016

Do you like food? Of course. But what if it's not you who chooses your food, but your food that chooses you? Dean Itsuji Saranillio investigates this question and many more in this #NYCAASC2016 highlighted workshop, "How has White Supremacy Shaped the Foods We Eat?"
Exciting news: the schedule for #NYCAASC2016 is out! Visit our lovely new website at nycaasc.com to view the schedule, as well as this year’s HYPE workshops. Time to start planning!

FINAL #NYCAASC2016 GIVEAWAY! We’ll be giving away seven (7) free 10th Anniversary Conference T-Shirts. This year’s conference theme, “Checkpoints”, is especially relevant, as we celebrate our tenth year of providing a space for dialogue and collaboration in A/P/A issues.

To be eligible for the giveaway, all you have to do is be registered on Eventbrite for the 10th Annual NYCAASC by this Wednesday, 4/20 at 11:59pm. That’s it! Registration is at nycaasc.com/registration

We will be announcing the winners of this giveaway at the conference. ***Please make sure you are attending on the day of, or you won’t be able to get a chance to win***. Thank you for participating in our giveaways, and we’re looking forward to seeing you on Saturday!

Front and back designs are pictured. Sizes vary depending on availability.

You've probably read about issues of race and gender in the news lately, but what does it all mean? This workshop will help you understand the role of racial, gender, and sexual identity in today's society from the standpoint of trans femme identity, and the violence that underlies this role.

Love comics? Ever wanted to create your own? Come join manga editor Anne Ishii and letterer-illustrator Hannah K. Lee at their delightful all-day workshop, "Drawing Ourselves in Mini-Comics and Zines", at #NYCAASC2016. Learn the techniques and strategies of designing mini-comics and zines with a narrative and artistic style that you can truly call "your own"!

We are so excited to announce that our Keynote Speaker at the 10th Annual New York City Asian American Student Conference is Cathy Dang, Executive Director of CAAAV: Organizing Asian Communities!

--------

Cathy has had a long history with grassroots organizing in addition to her work with CAAAV. For nearly a decade, she has led campaigns locally and nationally for just living and working conditions in immigrant and communities of color. Before becoming Executive Director, she served as CAAAV’s Lead Organizer. Cathy has roots in Queens, NY and Los Angeles, CA.

Caaav: Organizing Asian Communities, founded in 1986, is a pan-Asian grassroots organization that organizes low-income Asian immigrant communities in New York City toward institutional change. With over 300 members today, CAAAV continues to fight for racial, gender, and economic justice on local and national scales.

--------

Register for The 10th Annual NYCAASC: Checkpoints at nycaasc.com/registration

For more information about CAAAV: Organizing Asian Communities and their work, visit their website at http://caaav.org/

--- Featured Artist Spotlight #4 | Lee Hilado ---

Up-and-coming visual artist Lee Jacob Hilado will be showcasing an exhibit of paintings at the 10th Annual NYCAASC!  Lee is a Philippines-born visual artist, animator, and student currently based in NYC. His work has been featured in various exhibits, and has received a slew of accolades, including the Hostos Excellence in Animation in 2013 and, as recently as 2015, the Semifinal Illustrator Adobe Achievement Award.

Check out Lee’s Twitter at @jacobhilado

--- Featured Performance Spotlight #3 | Soomi Kim ---

Performing artist Soomi Kim will be giving a presentation about her critically acclaimed theatre “trilogy” - Lee/gendary, Dictee, and Chang(e) - at the 10th Annual NYCAASC! Her works explore historic Asian American visionaries such as Bruce Lee whose lives were tragically cut short. She will tackle how these radical and unfaltering figures are still relevant to inspiring today’s youth to fight against oppressive circumstances.

Check out Soomi’s Twitter at @soomdawg
Click link below to learn more about Soomi’s work!

--- Featured Artist Spotlight #1: Adriel Luis ---

Adriel Luis, artist, musician, poet, and much more, will be debuting his project “Customs and Arrivals” at the 10th Annual NYCAASC! Adriel’s performance, an engaging fusion of visuals, music, spoken word, and DJing, recounts his own journey with checkpoints, as he explores the personal and social connections (and disconnections) between Asian Americans and global Asian communities.

Check out Adriel’s Twitter at @drzzl

How can disenfranchised communities fight for justice? On Tuesday, March 8 at 7 pm, A/P/A Institute at NYU is hosting a screening of "East LA Interchange": a documentary about the struggles of working-class immigrant neighborhood Boyle Heights, upon which the U.S.'s busiest freeway was built. The film features narrator Danny Trejo and interviews with East LA natives such as will.i.am. The screening will be followed by a conversation with the director.

Admission is free. Info and register here: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/east-la-interchange-screening-and-discussion-registration-20707986144

Jes Tom brings their hilarious wit to our Open Mic in two weeks! Jes’s brilliant command of identity topics such as Asian America and queerness has made audiences throughout NYC rave with laughter, from Caroline’s on Broadway to the Gotham Comedy Club. NYCAASC has also had the pleasure of having Jes lead a workshop at last year’s conference about comedy as an innovative tool for radical activism. Provocative yet hysterical, their comedy is something you won’t want to miss!
